{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17595245","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17595245"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:01:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:01:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15343"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15343"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.51,0.11,0.3,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8034"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69874"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8034"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15343"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55330"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"8755"},{"type":"tags","id":"9833"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19515"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19518"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69874"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA patient presents with an elevated International Normalised Ratio (INR) of 2.8 (0.9-1.2) due to compensated liver cirrhosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the coagulation status in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Balanced coagulation state","Increased bleeding risk only","Increased thrombosis risk only","Combined bleeding and thrombosis risk","Normal coagulation state"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn liver dysfunction, there is decreased synthesis of both procoagulant and anticoagulant factors. While the INR may be elevated, suggesting a bleeding tendency, the patient is actually in a \u003Cstrong\u003Ebalanced coagulation state\u003C/strong\u003E as both pro- and anti-coagulant factors are reduced proportionally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is incorrect to assume there is only an \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased bleeding risk\u003C/strong\u003E or only an \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased thrombosis risk\u003C/strong\u003E. The concept of \u003Cstrong\u003Ecombined bleeding and thrombosis risk\u003C/strong\u003E overestimates the clinical impact. A \u003Cstrong\u003Enormal coagulation state\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as there are significant changes to coagulation factor levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe liver synthesizes most coagulation factors (II, V, VII, IX, X, XI, protein C, protein S) except Factor VIII and von Willebrand factor. An elevated INR primarily reflects decreased synthesis of vitamin K-dependent factors.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The liver synthesizes most coagulation factors except Factor VIII and von Willebrand factor","Liver dysfunction leads to decreased production of both procoagulant and anticoagulant factors","Elevated International Normalised Ratio (INR) indicates impaired coagulation factor synthesis","A balanced coagulation state may be disturbed in worsening liver function, infection, bleeding or acute kidney injury"],"references":["Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Gasmi B, Kleiner DE. Liver Histology: Diagnostic and Prognostic Features. Clin Liver Dis. 2020 Feb;24(1):61-74. doi: 10.1016/j.cld.2019.09.004. Epub 2019 Oct 31. PMID: 31753251; PMCID: PMC6986808","Edelson J, Basso JE, Rockey DC. Updated strategies in the management of acute variceal haemorrhage. Curr Opin Gastroenterol. 2021 May 1;37(3):167-172. doi: 10.1097/MOG.0000000000000723. PMID: 33769373; PMCID: PMC8691141"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55330"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15343"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55330","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55330"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T21:25:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-13T09:49:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8034"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69874"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id